                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d751">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">837.00/2850: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Cuba</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Reed</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Habana</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-10-04T10:00:00-05:00"
                            >October 4, 1930—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 11:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>121. My telegram No. 120, October 3, 10 a.m. Congress last night passed law
                    authorizing the President, whenever he deems it necessary, to suspend
                    constitutional guarantees for 20 days but only in city of Habana and adjacent
                    townships. Measure was warmly debated in both Houses. Vote in Senate 15 for, 5
                    against; in House 88 for, 10 against.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Reed</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
